        <div xml:id="AN16-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN16">
            <lg type="edition"><l>nāyuṭai mutunīrk kalitta tāmarait</l>
<l>tāti ṉalli yayalitaḻ puraiyu</l>
<l>māci laṅkai maṇimaru ḷavvāy</l>
<l>nāvoṭu navilā nakaipaṭu tīñcol</l>
<l>yāvarum viḻaiyum polantoṭip putalvaṉait</l>
<l>tērvaḻaṅku teruviṟ <choice><seg>ṟamiyōṟ</seg><seg>ṟamiyōrk</seg></choice> kaṇṭa</l>
<l>kūreyiṟ ṟarivai kuṟuki yāvaruṅ</l>
<l>kāṇuna <supplied>ri</supplied>ṉmaiyiṟ <choice><seg>cērttaṉaḷ</seg><seg>cettaṉaḷ</seg></choice> pēṇip</l>
<l>polaṅkalañ cumanta pūṇṭāṅ kiḷamulai</l>
<l>varuka māḷaveṉ ṉuyireṉap perituvantu</l>
<l>koṇṭaṉa ṇiṉṟōṭ <choice><seg>kaṇṭunilai</seg><seg>kaṇṭunilaic</seg></choice> <choice><seg>collēṉ</seg><seg>cellēṉ</seg></choice></l>
<l>mācil kuṟumaka ḷevaṉpē tuṟṟaṉai</l>
<l>nīyun tāyai yivaṟkeṉa yāṉṟaṟ</l>
<l>karaiya vantu viraivaṉaḷ kavaiik</l>
<l><choice><seg>kaḷavuṭaṉ</seg><seg>kaḷavuṭam</seg></choice> paṭunariṟ kaviḻntunilaṅ kiḷaiyā</l>
<l>nāṇi niṉṟō ṇilaikaṇ ṭiyāṉum</l>
<l><choice><seg>pēṇiṉe</seg><seg>pēṇiṉeṉ</seg></choice> ṉallaṉō makiḻna vāṉat</l>
<l>taṇaṅkaruṅ kaṭavu ḷaṉṉōṇiṉ</l>
<l>makaṉṟā yākal puraivatā leṉavē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>The young woman with sharp teeth</l>
<l>who saw alone in the <choice><seg>street, </seg><seg>street </seg></choice> where chariots <choice><seg>pass,</seg><seg>pass</seg></choice> </l>
<l rend="indent">	[my] son with a golden bracelet who is desired by everybody,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with spotless palms [and] gem-like<note place="foot">Here formula maṇi-maruḷ against custom has to be taken to refer to a red gem, as is confirmed by the old commentary that glosses pavaḷa maṇi, “coral gem”.</note> mouth</l>
<l rend="indent">	that resemble the outer petals<note place="foot">Do we have to take ayal-itaḻ as a sort of compound here, that is, literally “adjacent petals”?  Or is it a bracket construction, i.e. “the petals of the day lotus (tāmarai) that are adjacent to the white lotus (alli)? In any case the simile must denote white fingers on a red mouth.</note> of the white lotus with pollen</l>
<l rend="indent">	[and] the red lotus swollen in the old water that has otters,</l>
<l rend="indent">	with risible sweet words that are not pronounced [distinctly] by the tongue,</l>
<l>she approached</l>
<l>[and] <choice><seg>joined [him], </seg><seg>lingered, </seg></choice> judging there was no one to see.</l>
<l>[She with] young breasts that bear ornaments, laden with golden decoration,</l>
<l>seeing her stand [there] as she took [him] in<note place="foot">Here the old commentator understands literally that she is taking him up and to her breast (mulaiyiṭattuk koṇṭu niṉṟāḷ).</note>, greatly rejoicing,</l>
<l><choice><seg>saying: </seg><seg>saying </seg></choice> “you may come here, my life”,<note place="foot">Here tradition wants to read the other woman’s address to the little son.  However, the optative plus polite particle māḷa do not go well as an address to a toddler.  I think the point rather is a double encouragement, both times with endearment terms (eṉ uyir, kuṟu-makaḷ), from the lady of the house to the newly arriving second wife, who after all well may still be a child – a child bride − herself.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	I did not <choice><seg>talk about [her] station.</seg><seg>move from [my] position.</seg></choice> </l>
<l>When I hailed her<note place="foot">For yāṉ taṉ karaiya see the close parallel in NA 308.3, where HE reports how he addressed HER: yām taṉ karaiyavum nāṇinaḷ varuvōḷ.</note>: “spotless little girl, what are you confused for?</l>
<l rend="indent">	You too are a mother to him”,</l>
<l>she came in a hurry, in tears, embracing [me],</l>
<l>[and], overthrown by those who hold with [the practice of] Kaḷavu,</l>
<l>scratching the ground she stood ashamed,</l>
<l rend="indent">	and seeing her state I too</l>
<l>cherished her, did I not, o delightful man, thinking</l>
<l>that she, who is like a tormenting rare deity from heaven,</l>
<l>will become the mother of a son, it seems.</l>
<l rend="indent"></l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
